---
description: Next.js API route conventions. Applies to all API route handlers.
globs: ["src/app/api/**"]
alwaysApply: false
---

## API route structure
- One `route.ts` per endpoint in `src/app/api/[endpoint]/`.
- Export named HTTP method handlers: `GET`, `POST`, `PUT`, `DELETE`.
- Each handler receives `(request: NextRequest)` and returns a `NextResponse` or `Response`.

```typescript
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from "next/server";

export async function GET(request: NextRequest): Promise<Response> {
  const data = await fetchData();
  return NextResponse.json({ data });
}
```

## Input validation
- Validate request body and search params before processing.
- Use Zod schemas colocated in the route file for validation.
- Return 422 with descriptive errors on validation failure.
- Never trust user input — sanitise paths, IDs, and filenames.

## Error handling
- Wrap handler bodies in try/catch — never let unhandled errors escape.
- Return structured error responses:
  ```typescript
  return NextResponse.json(
    { error: { message: "Not found", code: "NOT_FOUND" } },
    { status: 404 }
  );
  ```
- Never expose internal errors, stack traces, or file paths to the client.
- Log the full error server-side; return only a safe message to the client.
- HTTP status codes: 400 bad input, 404 not found, 422 validation failed, 500 internal.

## Response shape
```typescript
// Success
{ data: T, meta?: { total: number } }

// Error
{ error: { message: string, code: string } }
```

## Security
- Validate and sanitise all path segments — prevent path traversal.
- Never read files outside the project root without explicit allowlisting.
- Set appropriate `Content-Type` and `Content-Disposition` headers for downloads.
- Never expose `.env` values, internal paths, or system info in responses.

## File locations
- API route handlers: `src/app/api/[resource]/route.ts`
- Dynamic segments: `src/app/api/[resource]/[id]/route.ts`
- Shared server utilities: `src/lib/`

## Do not
- Do not use Express patterns (`req`, `res`, middleware chains) — use Next.js App Router conventions.
- Do not instantiate database clients at the module level — use lazy initialisation if needed.
- Do not return raw file system errors to the client.
- Do not serve user-uploaded files without MIME type validation.
